{"/service/ndnp/wvu/batch_wvu_moore_ver01/data/sn86092392/00414187353/1910071301/0215.xml":{"full_text":"THE CEREDO ADVANCE.\nT. T. McDOUGAL, Publisher.\nCEREDO. WEST VIRGINIA.\nAmi about those flies-\u2014\u2022\nThere are no good flies except dead\nones.\nSome straw-hat symptoms are mani\nfesting themselves.\nAstronomers, on the other hand,\nlearn something new every day.\nJudging by some of the recent Ac\ntion. more novelists are of unsound\nxnlnd than are legally declared so.\nCandidates for parliament In Hun\ngary are being pelted with stale eggs.\nHas Hungary no cold-storage houses?\nSoon some nervous people will be\ngin worrying about what the comet\nwill do when it returns seventy-five\nyears hence.\nTho '\u2018Chanteelcr\u2019* cocktail Is tho\nlatest, but the man who drinks It\nprobably does not feel llko trowing\nthe next morning.\nThe price of skunk skins has ad\nvanced 100 per cent., so expect a big\nrise in several kinds of mink, seal and\nermine next winter.\nKissing Is safe, says a Boston phy\nsician. The young man's fancy will\nturn (his spring, no doubt, with far\nmore than Its usual Intensity.\nNew York suburban railroads have\nTalsed the rate to commuters. Here is\nnew Incentive for the flying-machine\nxnan to continue his activities.\nFrom Lynn comes a story of bread\nburled in dry sand and kept sound and\nSweet for 25 years. This seems to be\nanother hint for cold-storage men.\n\u201cDo not tell a boy how bad he Is,\u2019\u2019\naavs the superintendent of a boys'\nachool. No, he might get haughty\nbver having achieved such distinction.\nKansas will continue to raise corn\nand put money In the bank without\ngetting jealous or excited over dia\nmond discoveries in the neighborhood.\nRailroads are having trouble fixing\ntransportation charges on women\u2019s\ngats. They rre not heavy enough to\ngo by weight. Why not charge by the\nacre?\nThanks to the California experi\nmenters it is now possible to eat cacti\nand roses. It 11 be long before this\nprickly fodder takes the place* of meat\nand 'taters.\nThe scientists may prove or dis\nprove the dangers In kissing, but It\nwill take all the king\u2019s horses to stop\nit\u2014and no one seems to be rounding\nup horseB, either.\nThe Husbands' union should Inves\ntigate the case of the man whose wife\nbeat him with her fists, a stove poker,\na hammer, and then had him arrested\nfor assault and battery.\nAn engineer who ran his engine\nInto a train ahead of him says that\nthe Lord ordered him to do It, thus\npredicating another rase of orders\ngone awry in transmission.\nSchool children in various cities\nare voting against the firecracker and\nthe insane type of Fourth of July.\nThe children see the point when you\npresent it to them in the right way.\nSomebody has found out how to\nmake coffee from dandelion roots, but\nthere is no immediate danger that the\ndandelion crop will be a failure owing\nto the fact that a use has been found\nlor it.\nTbe Ornithologists\u2019 union of New\nYork has undertaken to try to restore\nthe wild pigeon. Perhaps members of\nthe Orni'l.ologiHts union have nothing j\nelse that may be regarded as worth\nwhile to do.\nIt Is an interesting and noteworthy\nfact ihat rince the promulgation of tho\nlaw of June, 19 )7. the effect of which\nIt to simplify tho formalities which are\nthe necessary preliminaries to mar\nrlage, th< re have been more weddings\nIn France than at any period since (be\nbeginning of \u2666he last century, with the\nexception rf the year 1813 and J872.\nIn the former of which men contracted\nunions to escape being sent off to\nfight, while In the latter many wed\nding, took place which had been de\nlaved by the war with (Jermany.\nThat, submarine vessels can make\nextended trips is shown by a recent\nexperience with the Viper, owned by\nthe I nitrd States, which, in command\nof a midshipman, ran 4V7 miles, from\nH point Off the North Carolina coast to\nAnnapolis. Hitherto no such attempt\nhas been made Of course, the voyage\nwas made on the surface, as suhmar\nfries dive only when such action is\nconsidered necessary. Ft.if ta.it the\nViper could go safely for such a dis\nlance, unaccompanied by any convoy\n1s taken to show that such craft nrs\ncapable of more Independent servlcv\nThan was supposed.\nIn Zurich. Switzerland, the people\nnave a custom of burning \u00abn effigy o*\nwinter In the streets, if it would help\nto bring winter to an end the custom\nmight well be adopted In o he* places\nThltia has tak*n another great step\ntoward western civilization and the\nen and;* 'Jon of its women. Thf\nrfnughtera of the Chinese minister at\nWashington have learned to make\n\u2666udge When the American schoolgirl\natmosphere get* into any home, hew\never orientalized, things are honod U\nbe obangfd.\nIn Maiden Hair Fern\nFERN EMBROIDERY.\nOna of the Prettiest Summer Decora\ntions for the Vacation Season\nTable Linen.\nIn nearly every summer homo the\nliving room is used as dining-room,\nthe meals being served on the center\nNEAT IDEAS IN TUB DRESS\nCostumes That Will Be Just the Thing\nWhen the Really Warm\nWeather Is With Us.\nThe first costume is In old blue\nlinen; three tucks are made nt the\nside of both skirt and bodice, the\nlatter has one wide tuck standing out\nover the shoulder. Buttons in sets of\nfour trim both bodice and skirt. The\ncuftB aro tucked all over, ho Is the col\nlar band.\nStraw hat turned up at the side and\ntrimmed with large flowers.\nMaterials required: 7 yards 15 inches\nwide, 3Vfc dozen buttons.\nThe other design, although made in\nlinen for summer w*ar. is a style that\nmay be reproduced just as well In any\nfirm wnolop material\nI lie color of our model Is sky blue;\nin Rtyle, It is a semi-princess, the front\nforming a panel.\nThe skirt is trimmed with a band of\nwide broderie nnglaise. from under\nwhich the linen is rut aw\u00bbry. The\nyoke is of piece embroidery, and is\noutlined with a fold of darker blue\nlinen under the etige. The oblong\npieces of embroidery form a further\ntrimming.\nI iat of pale blue fancy straw\ntrljnmed with a feather mount.\nMaterials required: 7 yards 40 Inc bee\nwide, 3 yards wide embroidery,\nyard piece embroidery for yoke, 1V4\nyards narrower insertion.\nStrawberry race Lotion.\nA good vegetable lotion to soften\nand whiten the skin 1\u00ab made by hu.l\nIng a quart of strawberries, mashing\nthem through a sieve, then adding two\ntablespoonfuls of strong vinegar to\neach quart of berries. Let It stand\nuntil It draws plenty of Juice and\nstrain through a fine muslin. Bottle\ntightly and in a cool place\ntable, which Is a feature of every sum\nmer cottage living room. The table li\nusually of some dark wood and set\nwith doilies and center piece instead\nof a large white cloth.\nSometimes a small lunch cloth la\nused, but usually the dollies are liked\nbest, as they are delightfully dainty\nin appearance. One of the coolest and\nmost charming combinations for the\nsummer table linen is green and white\nand no lovelier set of doilies could be\nimagined than one of fine, white linen\nbuttonholed In scallops in a pale sil\nvery green floss and decorated at in\ntervals with sprays of maiden hair\nfern. The design given may bo trans\nferred to the linen by means of car\nbon paper or a stamping outfit. It\nwould be much less work and very\npretty and unusual to have only ont\nspray of the fern on each dolly in\nstead of several, as very simple thing*\nare best in the summer. Three sprays\nof fern are given, one large one for\nthe plate and tumbler dollies.\nTo embroider tho fern use waish\nsilks of different shades of greon.\nEmbroider in long-and-short stitch and\nKe*>nlngton outline for the stem*.\nmgimn\u00aeKr.r\nTucking Is used a great deal on th\u00a9\nsummer gowns.\nSwiss fabrics are often worn wltL*\na colored slip.\nThis season ono finds entire coats\nand wraps of cretonne.\nThe elastic belts, In different\nwidths, are more popular than ever.\nCoarse Russian braid Is used a\ngreat deal for trimming coats nnd\ncapes.\nThe chantccler Is found env\nbroidered on the Instep of the latest\nsilk hosiery.\nThe tiniest of roses are used for\ntrimming caps of muslin or lace for\nthe baby.\nThe shoulder seam on the now shirt\nwaists Is much longer than that of\nlast season.\nLingerie embroidered with the all\npervading chantecler Is one of the\nfads of the hour.\nMany of the summer coats have\nlong rovers that cross and button be\nlow the waist line.\nA box-plaited quilling of net is the\nfinish at the wrist of a pretty sleeve\nseen recently.\nRibs of brttsa as well as of gilt and\nwhite enamel are seen In some of the\nsummer sunshndes.\nSeparate blouses of blnck net with\nlore Insertion are worn over an un-\nderblouse of white.\nGoing-away Coats.\nAn enterprising English dressmaker\nfllla In her spare time making \"going\naway coatH\u201d for little dogs. Thin\nwould indirnte (hat. the American\nheih. who carries in her nrrns the\nemail mite of a dog: la not the only\nfoolish woman in existence.\nIt is said that those little coats are\nfashioned of velvet or cloth to match\nthe bride's traveling gown, but to the\npractical they suggest only those very 1\nwonderful blankets we mado In our I\nlittle girl days for brother's wooden\nhorse.\nTockets, wc are told, for the hand\nkerchief and for four gutta-percha\nshoes for doggie finish the coat.\nCold Water Only.\nWhen the kitchen wall Is darker\nthan If should be and you strongly\nsuspect that part of the general gray\nness Is soot, there is n ready remedy\nIn cold water, provided the wall be\n|>v\u2018nfed or covered with enameled\npaper.\nThe paper should first he dusted\ndown with a feather or a clean e.oth\nwrung out of cold water until clean\nl)o net use v arm water, as If Vi likely\nto tin a the paper jeliow be sure to\nrinse the cloth as It geta dirty and\nalso to change the water frequent!*\nIf you would secure tha beat ceault*\nHOW SHE LOOKED AT IT.\nA life-insurance agent was trying\nlo induce young Mr. Nevermuch to\ntake out a policy.\n\u201cYou owe It to your wife to insure.\nThen If you die 6be's provided for.\u201d\nMrs. Nevermuch was duly im\npressed and urged her husband to\ncarry some insurance.\n\u201cWell, dearie,\u201d said the hard\npressed man, \u201cI'll explain this propo\nsition to you. Then if you want me\nto take out insurance, I will. It\u2019s like\nthis:: if i die soon you will still be\nyoung and good-looking enough to cop\nOut another bread-winner. And If I\nlive long enough the premiums on\nihe insurance would make the pay\nments on a pianola. Which will you\nhave?\u201d\nShe decided to take the piano\u2014and\nher chances.\nAnother Yarn.\n\"And you were once the tattooed\nman in the circus?\u201d said the sympa\nthetic housewife.\n\"Yes, mum,\u201d responded Sandy\nPikes, as he speared a buckwheat\ncake with his fork.\n\"And once you were caught in a\nrainstorm and all your colors ran to\ngether? Poor man! Were you out\nof a Job long?\u201d\nNo, indeed, mum. Dat very night\nI went around to de melodrama and\ngot a Job as a \u2018deep dyed villain.\u2019\nStill Invisible.\n\"By the way, old man,\u201d said the\nchronic toucher In lubricated tones,\nyou remember that five-spot I bor\nrowed from you laRt fall?\u201d\n\"Yes,\u201d responded his friend with a\nyawn, \"and every time I think of that\nfive-spot I think of the comet.\u201d\n\"That\u20193 a queer combination. What's\nthe similarity?\u201d\n'W hy, I've been looking for It for\nmonths and haven't seen It yet.\u201d\nTo Take No Chances.\nHamlar\u2014Why In the dickens have\nyou got that string tied around your\ntooth?\nAbsente\u2014To remind me that I must\nhave the tooth removed.\nHamlar\u2014But goodness gracious!\nWhy don\u2019t you do as ordinary people,\nand have the string tied around your\nfinger?\nAbsente (stiffly)\u2014Because, sir, I\ndon\u2019t care to have my finger removed.\nUP TO HIM.\nEdith\u2014I told papa that you wanted\nto aee him the next time you called.\nEdward\u2014What did he say?\nEdlfh\u2014He said all right\u2014be wasn\u2019t\nafraid of you.\nThe Hookworm.\nWho hocks up his wlfey.\nAnd never a sigh.\nDeserves with the angels\nIn Heaven to fly.\nExpensive.\nInquisitive Aunt Jessica\u2014Paul, do\nyou send a letter to your fiancee ev\nery day?\u201d\nPaul\u2014I should say not. If I sent\nher a letter as often as that I\u2019d be\nbroke In less than a week.\nInquisitive Aunt Jessica Why,\nDaul, what do you mean?\nPaul\u2014Simply this: My letters are\n*o valuable to her that she makes\nme send them all by registered mall.\nHow Hr Delivered Them.\n\"You want a Job as driver of the\nwagon, eh?\u201d said the grocer to the\nraw looking country youth. Yes, sir.\"\n\"Are you one of these fellows that\ncan stand and deliver the goods?\u201d \"I\ncan deliver \u2019em all right, mister, but 1\nalways sit down.\u201d\nRough on Algy.\n\"Algy swears he had a brain storm\nyesterday.\u201d\n\"Pshaw! I don't believe It.\u201d\n\"Why not?\u201d\nFor the same reason that I don\u2019t\nbelieve there can be rain where there\nis no moisture.\u201d\nJust 80.\n\"It took me three weeks,\u201d said the\ntraveling salesman, \"to get an audi\nence with the king. Put it was worth\n(he trouble. He conferred a decora\ntion upon me.\u201d\n\"Rooked an order did you?\u201d\nPerhaps.\n\"Who was It said, \u2018Life Is Just one I\na\u2014 thing i.fter another?\u201d\n\"Probably a fellow who mw a\nsnitch\u2019 trjlng to catch a blfn4\nUter.\u2019\nIN THE CRISP AND THE GLOW.\nIn the crisp and the glow of the morn\nIn*,\nWhen blue shines the sky overhead.\nlien the purple and rose of tlie dawn\nIn*\nAcross the horizon la spread\u2014\nThe Joy! The delight to be dtlng!\nTo feel the red blood In one's veins!\nMan\u2019s heart. In transcendas.t thanks\ngiving.\nGives voice to exuberant strains!\nIn the crisp and the glow of the morn\ning\u2014\nThe fresh wakened gold of the Jay\nAll weakness of yesterday scorning,\nKncouraged. he goes on his way.\nThe pleasure of daylight and strlvlkgt\nOf labor for those near and dear!\nIlls breast of Its misery shriving\nIn sunshine Inspiring and clear.\nIn the glow of the sun\u2019s slow retiring*\nThe crisp of the slow twilight\u2019s fall\u2014\nWith love all his eagerness firing\u2014\nSweet love for home, wife, child\nman\u2019s all!\nThe Joy! The delight! Compensation!\n^HIb soul soars on love-burdened wings!\nNo weariness mars the elation\nOf heart-gushing home-songs he sings!\n-Lurana W. Sheldon, In Nsw York\nTimes.\nMISUNDERSTOOD.\nLieutenant (showing party of vlat\ntors over battleship)\u2014This is th\u00ab\nquarter' deck.\nOne of the Party\u2014Q*el I thought\nit was all free!\nVery Seldom.\nYou seldom see a mortal wight.\nNo matter what his lahors,\nho doesn\u2019t And, In fate\u2019s despite,\nTne time to knock his neighbors.\nHOW IT HAPPENED.\nThe man who is always asking fool\nish questions approached the tough\nlooking citizen who was sitting on the\nsteps of his shanty nursing a sore\nhead.\n\u201cWhat\u2019s the matter with your head?\"\nasked Mr. Buttin.\n\u201cDepression in it.\u201d was the laconic\nresponse.\n\"What kind of a depression?\u201d\n\u201cBusiness depression.\u201d\nH\u2019m! That\u2019s a queer place for a\nbusiness depression. How did you\nget it?\u201d\nI rylng to meddle In other peo\nple s business. Now, trot on, stranger,\nbefore you get one of those depres\nsions yourself. They are catching.\u201d\nAnd Mr. Buttin \"trotted.\u201d\nPat Was Ready for Her.\nLady (who has Just returned with a\nlivery rig)\u2014I will never patronize\nyour stables again. That horse walked\nevery step of the way.\nPat (Celtic assistant)\u2014Yez didn\u2019t\nexpict the baste to ride, did ye*,\nmadam?\u2014National Monthly.\nSighs.\n\u201cWhat was the bridge of sighs?\u201d\nashed the woman who was looking at\nthe picture book.\n\u201cI suppose,\u201d replied Mrs. Flimgllt,\n\u201cthat is one of those games in which\nyou are obliged to make it spade#\nevery time.\u201d\nEnough Said.\n\"Rather a foxy move on the part ol\nMiss Trlppy\u2019s press agent.\u201d\n\u201cWhat was that?\u201d\nHe has sent out nn announcement\nthat a well known Jeweler makes all\nher costumes.\u201d\nACCIDENTAL STEP-MOTHER.\nMrg. Finnegan Shore, an\u2019 th\u2019 eat\nonly missed ma by about a foot.\nMr. ilnnegan\u2014Then had jwz gone\na atlp farther the children would have\nhad a atlp mother.\nThe Professor.\nHI* hair la long.\nHa piaya.quite well\nAnd has a noma\nLika a collage yell\nAUTOMATIC SYSTEM\nSCORES ON RIVALS\nIN TELEGRAPH\nTEST\nFLASHES 1000 WORD 8TORY OF\nTAFT'S SPEECH TO NEWSPA\nPERS IN ONE MINUTE\u2014HAND\nTRANSMITTED STORY CAME\nALONG HALF HOUR\nLATER.\nAt the Banners\u2019 Convention held re*\ncently in St. Louis, the Telepost Auto*\nmatic Telegraph Co. pulled off an In\nteresting little \u201cscoop\u201d on its rivals in\nconnection with the speech of Presi\ndent Taft. Before the newspaper men\npresent got outside the building a thou\nsand word story of the President\u2019s re\nception and speech at the convention\nhall was In Chicago, Indianapolis,\nSpringfield, Terre Haute and every\nother point In the Middle West to\nwhich the automatic system extends.\nWith It went a special message of\ngreeting to the farmers of America\ngiven by Mr. Taft for transmission\nover the automatic lines.\nThe feat was interesting, as demon\nstrating the possibilities of the auto\nmatic system in connection with rapid\npress work. In one minute from Ita\nstart, the 1000 word story was in the\ncities named, complete. From half to\na full hour later the press association\nreports Bent by hand telegraphy be\ngan to come along.\nThis achievement fulfills the claims\nmade for the Telepost recently by\nProfessor Roymn Hitchcock, former\nCurator of the Department of Science\nand Industries of the Smithsonian Insti\ntution. Testifying before a committeo\nof the N. Y. Legislature he said Peary\u2019s\n8,000 word story of his North Pole\nDiscovery could have been sent from.\nLabrador to the New York Times in\nten minutes by this system instead of\nthe three days it consumed in being\ntransmitted by hand.\nine leiepost transmits from 1000 to\n2000 words a minute, doing over any\none wire, the same volume of business\ndone over 66 wires operated by the\nMorse hand method of transmission,\nstill largely used throughout the coun\ntry.\nIn the States where the system Is.\ncommercially operating, it Is effecting*\na revolution with its rates of a quarter,\nhalf, and one cent a word regardless\nof time or distance.\nImportant extensions of the Tele\npost, it was said today on good author\nity, will be opened shortly between.\nChicago, Indianapolis and Detroit, To\nledo, Cleveland, Louisville, and other\ncities in Michigan, Ohio, Indiana and\nKentucky. The action last week of\nthe Senate Committee on%ths District\nof Columbia, favorably reporting the\nbill to admit the system to the National\nCapitol presages the early completion\nof its line between New York and\nWashington.\nNot Prepared to See.\nMarjorie\u2014Didn\u2019t you see the mouse?\nMadge\u2014Why, dear, I just couldn't\nsee it. I had my old stockings on.\nTo Maks Tabl\u00ae Cloths Last.\nTable linen is expensive. It costs\nmore today than ft did five years ago.\nWhen it begins to wear in holes, to\ncome from the wash with worn spots\nthat tell how soon it will be no good*\nno wonder the housewife despairs.\nCheap, common soaps full of caustics\nthat eat the linen are greatly to blame.\nEasy Task laundry soap is an enemy\nto dirt and stains and a friend to the\ntable linen. Get two five cent cakes;\ntry it, and if it does not surprise and\nsatisfy you the makers will returg\nyour money.\nGoodness is the only investment\nthat never fails.\u2014Thoreau.\ni. rF,URY T>\u25a0AVIS\u2019 PAIXKIM.FIt\n\u25a0*\"Jlit, safest a fid surest remedy for cramp*\nColic ami diarrhea. As a liniment for wounds aud\nSprains!Ill unequalled. 26c, 86c and 60c.\nCandor is ever the brightest gem of\ntrue criticism.\u2014Disraeli.\nMr*. Winslow\u2019s Soothing fiyrap.\nFor children teething, softens t he gums, rcdueetlts\n\u25a0ammauon.allays nam.cures wind colic. 26ca UtUis*\nUnsung songs cheer no hearts.\u2014A.\nWilliams.\nW DODD'S\n^KIDNEY\nh, PILLS Jk\nAk' V\\\\\\v>>>,s\u00a3*\nV^&PNEVj1^,'\niltK M A^l?\u00a3 A?\nKLR\u00bb\u00bbw\u00abnaaf'\nl I tfNfci.55lAnprCS ^firtlll' A\n\n\u25a0Z5 \u201cGunr***!\nW. L. DOUGLAS\nSHOES\n\u20225.*4.*3.50.*3. \u00bb2.BO A tl\nTHE 8TANDARD\nFOR 30 YEARS.\nMillion* of IMR w*\u00bbr\nW. L. Dmiflai ih*M bo\nunn lhay *r* lh* low\nM price*, Quality eon\n\u2022iderad, In the world.\nMado upon honor,of lb*\nbest Wat Sera, b* lb*\nmoat shilled workmen,\nin all the late*\u00ab fashion*.\nW. L. OPnptaa $S.OO\n*\"d $4.00 shoe* equal\n\u2022\u25a0\u2022lorn Bench Work\nrotting $41.00 In $0.00.\ntct\u00bb'Sho*\u00bb,$3.$2.fiOA$2","height":"25908","width":"19125"}}
